<DOC><DOCNO> AP880529-0018 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-29-88 1144EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh-Floods     05-29 0267</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bangladesh-Floods,0276</SECOND><HEAD>Five Dead, Thousands Displaced by Flooding</HEAD><DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   At least five people have died andthousands have been forced to flee their homes because of floodingin Bangladesh's northeastern districts, government officials andnews reports said Sunday.   Last summer, more than one-quarter of the nation's 105 millionpeople were forced to flee the worst flooding in 70 years.   This year, heavy rains and the annual snow melt from theHimalaya mountains have sent the Surma and Kushiara rivers in thenortheastern districts of Sylhet and Sunamganj over their banks.   Government officials in Sylhet, 100 miles northeast of Dhaka,said Sunday that three people died when their house was washed awayand that two others drowned.   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said atleast 30,000 people have been marooned. Thousands of others madetheir way to relief camps and were being aided by local Red Crossofficers and government agencies.   The government-owned Bengalai-language Dainik Bangla newspapersaid at least 500,000 people had been driven from their homesduring the past week of rain and flooding.   Thousands of acres of tea plantations and rice paddies werereported inundated. Rice is a staple food in Bangladesh.   Some market towns in Sunamganj District were reported under twofeet of water.   Schools in both districts have been closed, and some have beenconverted to relief centers for the homeless, the officials said.   The government officials said flights were disrupted at theairport at Sylhet on Saturday.   Last year, two months of serious flooding killed about 1,500people and destroyed thousands of acres of crops.</TEXT></DOC>